8816 .pru_bind = sctp_bind,
8817 .pru_connect = sctp_connect,
8818 .pru_connect2 = pru_connect2_notsupp,
8819 .pru_control = in_control,
8820 .pru_detach = sctp_detach,
8821 .pru_disconnect = sctp_disconnect,
8822 .pru_listen = sctp_listen,
8823 .pru_peeraddr = sctp_peeraddr,
8824 .pru_rcvd = NULL,
8825 .pru_rcvoob = pru_rcvoob_notsupp,
8826 .pru_send = sctp_sendm,
8827 .pru_sense = pru_sense_null,
8828 .pru_shutdown = sctp_shutdown,
8829 .pru_sockaddr = sctp_ingetaddr,
8830 .pru_sosend = sctp_sosend,
8831 .pru_soreceive = sctp_soreceive,
8832 .pru_sopoll = sopoll
8833#elif defined(_WIN32) && !defined(__Userspace__)
8834 sctp_abort,
8835 sctp_accept,

8839 pru_connect2_notsupp,
8840 NULL,

8843 sctp_listen,

8859#elif !defined(__Userspace__)
8860int
8861sctp_usrreq(so, req, m, nam, control)
8862 struct socket *so;
8863 int req;
8864 struct mbuf *m, *nam, *control;
8865{
8866 struct proc *p = curproc;
8867 int error;
8868 int family;
8869 struct sctp_inpcb *inp = (struct sctp_inpcb *)so->so_pcb;
8870
8871 error = 0;
8872 family = so->so_proto->pr_domain->dom_family;
8873 if (req == PRU_CONTROL) {
8874 switch (family) {
8875 case PF_INET:
8876 error = in_control(so, (long)m, (caddr_t)nam,
8877 (struct ifnet *)control);
8878 break;
8879#ifdef INET6
8880 case PF_INET6:
8881 error = in6_control(so, (long)m, (caddr_t)nam,
8882 (struct ifnet *)control, p);
8883 break;
8884#endif
8885 default:
8886 SCTP_LTRACE_ERR_RET(inp, NULL, NULL, SCTP_FROM_SCTP_USRREQ, EAFNOSUPPORT);
8887 error = EAFNOSUPPORT;
8888 }
8889 return (error);
8890 }
8891 switch (req) {
8892 case PRU_ATTACH:
8893 error = sctp_attach(so, family, p);
8894 break;
8895 case PRU_DETACH:
8896 error = sctp_detach(so);
8897 break;
8898 case PRU_BIND:
8899 if (nam == NULL) {
8900 SCTP_LTRACE_ERR_RET(inp, NULL, NULL, SCTP_FROM_SCTP_USRREQ, EINVAL);
8901 return (EINVAL);
8902 }
8903 error = sctp_bind(so, nam, p);
8904 break;
8905 case PRU_LISTEN:
8906 error = sctp_listen(so, p);
8907 break;
8908 case PRU_CONNECT:
8909 if (nam == NULL) {
8910 SCTP_LTRACE_ERR_RET(inp, NULL, NULL, SCTP_FROM_SCTP_USRREQ, EINVAL);
8911 return (EINVAL);
8912 }
8913 error = sctp_connect(so, nam, p);
8914 break;
8915 case PRU_DISCONNECT:
8916 error = sctp_disconnect(so);
8917 break;
8918 case PRU_ACCEPT:
8919 if (nam == NULL) {
8920 SCTP_LTRACE_ERR_RET(inp, NULL, NULL, SCTP_FROM_SCTP_USRREQ, EINVAL);
8921 return (EINVAL);
8922 }
8923 error = sctp_accept(so, nam);
8924 break;
8925 case PRU_SHUTDOWN:
8926 error = sctp_shutdown(so);
8927 break;
8928
8929 case PRU_RCVD:
8930 /*
8931 * For Open and Net BSD, this is real ugly. The mbuf *nam
8932 * that is passed (by soreceive()) is the int flags c ast as
8933 * a (mbuf *) yuck!
8934 */
8935 break;
8936
8937 case PRU_SEND:
8938 /* Flags are ignored */
8939 {
8940 struct sockaddr *addr;
8941
8942 if (nam == NULL)
8943 addr = NULL;
8944 else
8945 addr = mtod(nam, struct sockaddr *);
8946
8947 error = sctp_sendm(so, 0, m, addr, control, p);
8948 }
8949 break;
8950 case PRU_ABORT:
8951 error = sctp_abort(so);
8952 break;
8953
8954 case PRU_SENSE:
8955 error = 0;
8956 break;
8957 case PRU_RCVOOB:
8958 SCTP_LTRACE_ERR_RET(inp, NULL, NULL, SCTP_FROM_SCTP_USRREQ, EAFNOSUPPORT);
8959 error = EAFNOSUPPORT;
8960 break;
8961 case PRU_SENDOOB:
8962 SCTP_LTRACE_ERR_RET(inp, NULL, NULL, SCTP_FROM_SCTP_USRREQ, EAFNOSUPPORT);
8963 error = EAFNOSUPPORT;
8964 break;
8965 case PRU_PEERADDR:
8966 error = sctp_peeraddr(so, nam);
8967 break;
8968 case PRU_SOCKADDR:
8969 error = sctp_ingetaddr(so, nam);
8970 break;
8971 case PRU_SLOWTIMO:
8972 error = 0;
8973 break;
8974 default:
8975 break;
8976 }
8977 return (error);
8978}
8979
8980#endif
8981#endif

8983#if defined(__Userspace__)
8984int
8985register_recv_cb(struct socket *so,
8986 int (*receive_cb)(struct socket *sock, union sctp_sockstore addr, void *data,
8987 size_t datalen, struct sctp_rcvinfo, int flags, void *ulp_info))
8988{
8989 struct sctp_inpcb *inp;
8990
8991 inp = (struct sctp_inpcb *) so->so_pcb;
8992 if (inp == NULL) {
8993 return (0);
8994 }
8995 SCTP_INP_WLOCK(inp);
8996 inp->recv_callback = receive_cb;
8997 SCTP_INP_WUNLOCK(inp);
8998 return (1);
8999}
9000
9001int
9002register_send_cb(struct socket *so, uint32_t sb_threshold, int (*send_cb)(struct socket *sock, uint32_t sb_free, void *ulp_info))
9003{
9004 struct sctp_inpcb *inp;
9005
9006 inp = (struct sctp_inpcb *) so->so_pcb;
9007 if (inp == NULL) {
9008 return (0);
9009 }
9010 SCTP_INP_WLOCK(inp);
9011 inp->send_callback = send_cb;
9012 inp->send_sb_threshold = sb_threshold;
9013 SCTP_INP_WUNLOCK(inp);
9014 /* FIXME change to current amount free. This will be the full buffer
9015 * the first time this is registered but it could be only a portion
9016 * of the send buffer if this is called a second time e.g. if the
9017 * threshold changes.
9018 */
9019 return (1);
9020}

9022int
9023register_ulp_info (struct socket *so, void *ulp_info)
9024{
9025 struct sctp_inpcb *inp;
9026
9027 inp = (struct sctp_inpcb *) so->so_pcb;
9028 if (inp == NULL) {
9029 return (0);
9030 }
9031 SCTP_INP_WLOCK(inp);
9032 inp->ulp_info = ulp_info;
9033 SCTP_INP_WUNLOCK(inp);
9034 return (1);
9035}
9036
9037int
9038retrieve_ulp_info (struct socket *so, void **pulp_info)
9039{
9040 struct sctp_inpcb *inp;
9041
9042 if (pulp_info == NULL) {
9043 return (0);
9044 }
9045
9046 inp = (struct sctp_inpcb *) so->so_pcb;
9047 if (inp == NULL) {
9048 return (0);
9049 }
9050 SCTP_INP_RLOCK(inp);
9051 *pulp_info = inp->ulp_info;
9052 SCTP_INP_RUNLOCK(inp);
9053 return (1);
9054}
